================================================================================
1. INFINITE BOARD WITH PAN/ZOOM
================================================================================

PRD Requirement: Infinite board with smooth pan/zoom.

WHERE IT LIVES:
- BoardCanvas.tsx — Konva Stage handles all pan/zoom

HOW IT WORKS:
- The entire canvas is a Konva Stage. There are no boundaries — users can pan
  infinitely in any direction.
- Zoom: Mouse wheel fires handleWheel(). Each tick multiplies scale by 1.05.
  Scale is clamped between 0.4 (40%) and 2.5 (250%).
- Zoom center is the mouse pointer. The math:
    1. Convert pointer screen coords to world coords:
       mousePointTo = (pointer - stagePos) / oldScale
    2. After scaling, reposition stage so the same world point stays under cursor:
       newPos = pointer - mousePointTo * newScale
  This keeps zoom feeling natural — you zoom into what you're looking at.
- Pan: Hold Space + drag, or middle-mouse drag. The stage position updates via
  setStagePos(), and the viewport reference (viewportRef) updates so other
  systems (culling, AI viewport) know the current view.

KEY DETAIL FOR INTERVIEW:
"We use Konva's Stage as our infinite canvas. Zoom is pointer-relative — we
convert screen coordinates to world coordinates, apply the new scale, then
reposition the stage so the point under the cursor stays fixed. Pan is
space+drag. The scale is clamped to [0.4, 2.5] for usability."


================================================================================
2. STICKY NOTES
================================================================================

PRD Requirement: Create, edit text, change colors.

WHERE IT LIVES:
- StickyItem component in BoardCanvas.tsx (lines 364-476)
- handleAddSticky() in BoardClient.tsx
- Color picker in sidebar (BoardClient.tsx)

HOW IT WORKS:
- Creation: User clicks "Add Sticky" in sidebar. handleAddSticky() computes the
  viewport center in world coordinates, then writes a new doc to Firestore:
    addDoc(itemsRef, {
      type: "sticky", text: "New note", x, y,
      width: 160, height: 160, fill: "#C9E4DE",
      createdBy: uid, updatedAt: serverTimestamp()
    })
- Rendering: StickyItem is a React.memo component containing a Konva Rect
  (rounded corners, shadow) + Konva Text (word-wrapped).
- Editing: Double-click triggers an HTML textarea overlay positioned at the
  sticky's screen coordinates. On blur or Enter (not Shift+Enter), the text
  persists via updateDoc(). The textarea is rendered in the DOM layer above the
  Konva canvas.
- Color: Select the sticky, then click a color swatch in the sidebar. This calls
  updateDoc() with the new fill value. 7 preset colors available.

KEY DETAIL FOR INTERVIEW:
"Sticky notes are Konva Rect + Text groups. Text editing uses an HTML textarea
overlay — not Konva's built-in text editing — because Konva's text input
handling is limited. The overlay is positioned using the item's world-to-screen
coordinate transform."


================================================================================
3. SHAPES (RECT, CIRCLE, LINE, HEART)
================================================================================

PRD Requirement: Rectangles, circles, lines with solid colors.

WHERE IT LIVES:
- RectItem, CircleItem, LineItem, HeartItem in BoardCanvas.tsx
- handleAddRect/Circle/Line/Heart in BoardClient.tsx

HOW IT WORKS:
- Each shape type has its own React.memo component with custom equality function.
- Rect: Konva Rect with stroke, shadow. Default 200x120, fill #C6DEF1.
- Circle: Konva Ellipse (radius-based, not diameter). Default 150x150.
- Line: Konva Line with two points [x1, y1, x2, y2] relative to the group
  position. When selected, draggable endpoint circles appear so users can
  reshape the line.
- Heart: SVG path rendered via Konva Path. Normalized to 100x100 viewport, then
  scaled by width/height. Default 120x120, fill #FFD7D7.

ALL SHAPES SUPPORT:
- Move (drag)
- Resize (Konva Transformer)
- Rotate (Konva Transformer rotation handle)
- Color change (sidebar color picker)
- Selection (click to select, orange stroke)

KEY DETAIL FOR INTERVIEW:
"All shape components are wrapped in React.memo with a custom equality function
called boardItemEqual that only compares render-relevant fields like x, y, width,
height, fill, text, rotation — not metadata fields like createdBy or updatedAt.
This prevents unnecessary re-renders when only metadata changes."


================================================================================
4. CONNECTORS (LINES/ARROWS)
================================================================================

PRD Requirement: Lines/arrows connecting objects.

WHERE IT LIVES:
- ConnectorLine component in BoardCanvas.tsx
- Connector type in src/types/board.ts
- Connection logic in BoardClient.tsx

HOW IT WORKS:
- Each connector stores fromId and toId (references to board items), style
  ("line" or "arrow"), and color.
- Rendering: ConnectorLine calculates edge intersection points using
  getItemBounds() and getEdgePoint(). This finds where the connection line
  intersects the perimeter of each item, so lines connect at the edges — not
  the center.
- getEdgePoint uses the angle between item centers and the item's aspect ratio
  to determine which edge (top, bottom, left, right) the line exits from, then
  calculates the exact intersection point.

CREATION FLOW:
1. User clicks "Connect" tool in sidebar → activeTool = "connect"
2. Click first item → connectSourceId is set, item gets blue stroke
3. Mouse moves → preview line draws from source to cursor position
4. Click second item → writes connector doc to Firestore
5. Firestore onSnapshot fires → ConnectorLine renders

CASCADE DELETE:
When a board item is deleted, all connectors with fromId or toId matching that
item are also deleted in the same writeBatch. This ensures no orphaned connectors.

KEY DETAIL FOR INTERVIEW:
"Connectors dynamically calculate edge intersection points based on item bounds
and angles. When you delete an item, all its connectors are cascade-deleted in
the same Firestore writeBatch for atomicity."


