5. STANDALONE TEXT ELEMENTS
================================================================================

PRD Requirement: Standalone text elements.

WHERE IT LIVES:
- TextItem component in BoardCanvas.tsx (lines 500-609)
- handleAddText in BoardClient.tsx

HOW IT WORKS:
- Text items render as a transparent hit-rect + Konva Text (no background, no
  shadow — clean text appearance).
- Default: 200px wide, auto-height, fill #1c1917, fontSize 20.
- Creation: handleAddText() creates the item at viewport center, then sets
  pendingTextEditId to immediately open the text editor.
- Editing: Double-click opens HTML textarea overlay (same pattern as stickies).
- Font size: When a text item is selected, the sidebar shows a font size picker
  with options [12, 16, 20, 28, 40].
- Text color: Uses the same color picker as shapes, but applies to fill.

KEY DETAIL FOR INTERVIEW:
"Text items differ from stickies — they have no background rect or shadow, just
clean text. They also support configurable font sizes. On creation, we
immediately open the editor so the user can start typing."


================================================================================
6. FRAMES
================================================================================

PRD Requirement: Group and organize content areas.

WHERE IT LIVES:
- FrameItem component in BoardCanvas.tsx (lines 630-700+)
- Frame tool state in BoardClient.tsx

HOW IT WORKS:
- Frames are border-only containers with an editable title.
- Default: 300x200, indigo (#6366f1) stroke.
- Creation (two modes):
  1. Sidebar button: Creates frame at viewport center with default size.
  2. Frame tool: Set activeTool="frame", then click-and-drag on canvas to draw
     a frame at custom position/size. Canvas shows crosshair cursor in this mode.
- Title editing: Double-click the frame title → HTML <input> overlay (single-line,
  unlike sticky's multi-line textarea). Enter or blur commits the title.
- Frames don't automatically group child items — they're visual containers only.
  The AI templates use frames as labeled quadrants (SWOT, retro columns).

KEY DETAIL FOR INTERVIEW:
"Frames use a single-line input for title editing, unlike stickies which use
textareas. The frame tool lets you click-and-drag to draw custom-sized frames.
Frames are visual containers — they don't have automatic child grouping."


================================================================================
7. TRANSFORMS (MOVE, RESIZE, ROTATE)
================================================================================

PRD Requirement: Move, resize, rotate objects.

WHERE IT LIVES:
- Drag handling in BoardCanvas.tsx (onDragStart/Move/End)
- Konva Transformer in BoardCanvas.tsx
- handleTransformEnd callback

HOW IT WORKS:
- Move: Konva's built-in draggable property. On dragEnd, the final position is
  persisted to Firestore via updateDoc().
- Resize/Rotate: Konva Transformer component wraps selected items. It provides
  resize handles (corners/edges) and a rotation handle. On transformEnd:
    1. Read the node's new scaleX, scaleY, rotation, x, y from Konva
    2. Compute new width = originalWidth * scaleX, height = originalHeight * scaleY
    3. Reset node scale to 1 (Konva uses scale for transform preview)
    4. Persist width, height, rotation, x, y to Firestore
- handleTransformEnd is a stable useCallback (not recreated per render) to avoid
  perf issues with Konva event handlers.
- Rotation is persisted in degrees and survives page refresh.

GROUP DRAG:
When multiple items are selected and you drag one, all selected items move
together. The code computes the delta from the dragged item and applies it to all
other selected items.

KEY DETAIL FOR INTERVIEW:
"Konva's Transformer handles resize/rotate visually using scale transforms. On
transformEnd, we convert scale back to absolute width/height, reset the node
scale to 1, and persist the final dimensions. This is because Konva's Transformer
works via scale — we normalize back to absolute values for storage."


================================================================================
8. SELECTION (SINGLE, MULTI, DRAG-BOX)
================================================================================

PRD Requirement: Single and multi-select (shift-click, drag-to-select).

HOW IT WORKS:
- Single click: Sets selectedIds = [clickedItemId]. Orange stroke appears.
- Shift+click: Toggles item in/out of selectedIds array.
- Drag selection box: In "select" tool mode, clicking and dragging on the canvas
  background draws a selection rectangle. On mouse-up, all items whose bounds
  intersect the selection box are added to selectedIds.
- Click empty canvas: Clears selection (selectedIds = []).
- Selected connector: Separate state (selectedConnectorId) — only one connector
  can be selected at a time, shown with different visual treatment.

KEY DETAIL FOR INTERVIEW:
"We track selectedIds as a string array. The selection box checks item bounds
intersection. Connectors have their own separate selection state because they're
a different entity type."


================================================================================
9. OPERATIONS (DELETE, DUPLICATE, COPY/PASTE)
================================================================================

PRD Requirement: Delete, duplicate, copy/paste.

DELETE:
- Keyboard: Delete/Backspace key when items selected
- Sidebar: Delete button
- Writes a Firestore writeBatch that deletes all selected items AND all
  connectors touching those items (cascade delete)
- Single batch = atomic operation

DUPLICATE (Cmd/Ctrl+D):
- Creates copies of all selected items with a +20px offset on both axes
- New items get fresh IDs and the current user's uid as createdBy
- Uses a single writeBatch for atomicity

COPY (Cmd/Ctrl+C):
- Stores selected items in a clipboardItems state variable (in-memory, not
  system clipboard)
- Resets pasteOffsetCountRef to 0

PASTE (Cmd/Ctrl+V):
- Calculates viewport center in world coordinates
- Finds bounding box center of clipboard items
- Offsets paste by (pasteCount + 1) * 20px on each axis
- Each subsequent paste shifts 20px further (stagger pattern)
- Creates new items with fresh IDs via writeBatch

KEY DETAIL FOR INTERVIEW:
"Copy/paste uses in-memory clipboard state, not the system clipboard. Each paste
operation offsets 20px further than the previous one to prevent items stacking
on top of each other. All batch operations use Firestore writeBatch for
atomicity."


================================================================================
10. REAL-TIME SYNC
================================================================================

PRD Requirement: Object creation/modification appears instantly for all users.
Target: < 100ms object sync latency.

WHERE IT LIVES:
- Firestore onSnapshot listeners in BoardClient.tsx (lines 213-280)
- Items subscription and connectors subscription

HOW IT WORKS:
- On board mount, the client subscribes to two Firestore onSnapshot listeners:
  1. boards/{boardId}/items → all board items
  2. boards/{boardId}/connectors → all connectors
- When ANY user creates/modifies/deletes an item, Firestore pushes the change
  to ALL subscribed clients in real-time.
- The listener callback uses structural sharing: it compares each incoming item
  against the previous state. If render-relevant fields haven't changed, it
  reuses the same object reference. This prevents React from re-rendering
  unchanged items.

WRITE PATTERN:
- All mutations (create, update, delete) go through Firestore SDK methods:
  addDoc, updateDoc, deleteDoc, writeBatch
- Firestore handles conflict resolution automatically (last-write-wins)
- serverTimestamp() is used for updatedAt fields

KEY DETAIL FOR INTERVIEW:
"Real-time sync uses Firestore's onSnapshot which pushes changes to all clients
in real-time. We use structural sharing in the snapshot callback — comparing
render-relevant fields and reusing object references for unchanged items. This
prevents unnecessary React re-renders when an item's metadata changes but its
visual properties haven't."


================================================================================
11. MULTIPLAYER CURSORS
================================================================================

PRD Requirement: Multiplayer cursors with names, real-time movement.
Target: < 50ms cursor sync latency.

WHERE IT LIVES:
- RTDB subscription in BoardClient.tsx (lines 1054-1110)
- Cursor rendering in BoardCanvas.tsx
- CURSOR_THROTTLE_MS = 16 (line 24, BoardCanvas.tsx)

HOW IT WORKS:
- Each client writes its cursor position to Firebase Realtime Database at:
  /boards/{boardId}/presence/{userId}-{sessionId}
- Data written: { name, color, cursorX, cursorY, isOnline, lastActive }
- Cursor position is throttled to 16ms (60fps) to balance smoothness vs writes.
- Color is deterministic — derived from a hash of the userId, so each user
  always gets the same color.
- All clients subscribe to the presence path via RTDB onValue(). When any cursor
  moves, all other clients see it in real-time.
- Cursor rendering: Konva arrow/circle + text label positioned at the remote
  user's world coordinates.

WHY RTDB NOT FIRESTORE:
- RTDB is optimized for high-frequency, low-latency writes (cursors move
  constantly). Firestore has higher per-write latency and cost. Cursor data is
  ephemeral — it doesn't need Firestore's querying or persistence guarantees.

KEY DETAIL FOR INTERVIEW:
"Cursor sync uses Firebase Realtime Database, not Firestore, because RTDB has
lower latency and is designed for high-frequency ephemeral writes. We throttle
cursor updates to 16ms (60fps). Cursor colors are deterministic — derived from
a hash of the user ID."


================================================================================
12. PRESENCE AWARENESS
================================================================================

PRD Requirement: Clear indication of who's currently on the board.

HOW IT WORKS:
- The sidebar shows an "Online" section listing active users with their names
  and colored indicators.
- Presence is maintained via RTDB with three mechanisms:
  1. Heartbeat: Every 8 seconds, clients update their presence entry with
     { lastActive: serverTimestamp(), isOnline: true }
  2. onDisconnect: Firebase's onDisconnect().remove() automatically deletes the
     presence entry when the client's connection drops.
  3. Stale filtering: When rendering the online list, entries older than 20
     seconds (STALE_PRESENCE_MS) are filtered out.
- Session ID: Each tab gets a unique session ID, so the same user in multiple
  tabs appears as separate cursors.

KEY DETAIL FOR INTERVIEW:
"Presence uses a three-layer system: an 8-second heartbeat for active clients,
onDisconnect().remove() for clean disconnections, and 20-second stale filtering
as a fallback. Each browser tab gets a unique session ID so a user in multiple
tabs appears correctly."


================================================================================
13. CONFLICT RESOLUTION
================================================================================

PRD Requirement: Handle simultaneous edits (last-write-wins acceptable).

HOW IT WORKS:
- The app uses Firestore's native last-write-wins semantics. There is no custom
  conflict detection or resolution — the codebase contains multiple comments
  reading "Firestore sync will reconcile" at error catch blocks.
- When two users edit the same item simultaneously:
  1. Both writes go to Firestore independently
  2. The write that reaches Firestore last overwrites the first
  3. Both clients receive the final state via onSnapshot
  4. All clients converge to the same state
- serverTimestamp() ensures consistent ordering on the backend.

- For drag operations: the useDragBroadcast hook writes intermediate positions
  to RTDB during the drag (every 50ms), then persists the final position to
  Firestore on dragEnd. Other clients see the drag in progress via RTDB and
  the final state via Firestore.

- Priority order for rendering an item's position:
  1. Local drag state (if this client is dragging it)
  2. Remote drag state from RTDB (if another client is dragging it)
  3. Firestore persisted state (ground truth)

KEY DETAIL FOR INTERVIEW:
"We use Firestore's native last-write-wins. During drags, we broadcast
intermediate positions to RTDB at 50ms intervals so other users see smooth
movement. On drag end, the final position is persisted to Firestore. Position
rendering uses a priority chain: local drag > remote RTDB drag > Firestore state."


================================================================================
14. DISCONNECT/RECONNECT RESILIENCE
================================================================================

PRD Requirement: Graceful disconnect/reconnect handling.

HOW IT WORKS:
- onDisconnect().remove() — Firebase automatically removes the user's presence
  entry when their WebSocket connection drops. No server-side logic needed.
- Firestore onSnapshot listeners automatically reconnect when the network
  returns. The listener receives a fresh snapshot of the current state, so the
  client is instantly up-to-date.
- RTDB onValue listeners also auto-reconnect with Firebase's built-in
  reconnection logic.
- Stale presence TTL (20 seconds) catches edge cases where onDisconnect doesn't
  fire (e.g., device sleep, crash).
- Retry logic: If the initial RTDB presence subscription gets a permission_denied
  error, the client retries once after 500ms. This handles race conditions where
  the board membership hasn't propagated yet.

KEY DETAIL FOR INTERVIEW:
"Firebase handles reconnection automatically for both Firestore and RTDB. Our
onDisconnect handler cleans up presence, and the 20-second stale TTL is a safety
net. The onSnapshot listener receives the full current state on reconnect, so
clients always converge."


================================================================================
15. BOARD PERSISTENCE
================================================================================

PRD Requirement: Board state survives all users leaving and returning.

HOW IT WORKS:
- ALL board items and connectors are stored in Firestore (persistent NoSQL
  database). RTDB is only used for ephemeral data (cursors, in-progress drags).
- When all users leave and return later:
  1. Firestore still has every item, connector, and board metadata
  2. onSnapshot listeners fire with the full document set
  3. The board renders exactly as it was left
  4. RTDB presence entries are gone (cleaned up by onDisconnect), but that's
     expected — presence should only show currently-online users

KEY DETAIL FOR INTERVIEW:
"Firestore is our persistent layer — all items and connectors survive indefinitely.
RTDB is only for ephemeral data like cursors and active drags. This separation
means the board is always recoverable even if RTDB data is lost."


