17. BOARD MANAGEMENT & INVITE FLOW
================================================================================

WHERE IT LIVES:
- Board CRUD: src/lib/boards.ts
- Home page: src/app/page.tsx
- Board access check: BoardClient.tsx (lines 157-196)

BOARD CREATION:
- User enters board name on home page → createBoard(name, uid, email)
- Writes to Firestore: boards/{newId} with members: [uid], memberEmails: [email]
- Redirects to /board/{newId}

BOARD DASHBOARD:
- Shows all boards where the user is a member
- Each board card displays: name, member avatars (up to 3 + "+N"), member count,
  relative last-updated time ("5m ago")
- Owner can delete their boards

INVITE FLOW:
1. Board member clicks "Share" → copies URL: /board/{boardId}?invite=true
2. Recipient opens URL → if not authenticated, sees login prompt
3. If authenticated but not a member → sees "Join Board" button
4. Click "Join Board" → joinBoard(boardId, uid, email) adds user to members array
5. Firestore rules allow non-members to add themselves to the members array
   specifically for this invite flow
6. Page refreshes to "ok" state and loads the board

KEY DETAIL FOR INTERVIEW:
"The invite flow uses a URL query parameter (?invite=true). Firestore security
rules specifically allow non-members to add themselves to a board's members array
when joining. This is the only write operation a non-member can perform."


================================================================================
18. PERFORMANCE (60 FPS, 500+ OBJECTS, 5+ USERS)
================================================================================

PRD Targets: 60 FPS, 500+ objects, < 100ms sync, < 50ms cursor, 5+ users.

VIEWPORT CULLING:
- Only items within the current viewport + 200px buffer are rendered.
- viewportWorldRect is computed via useMemo from stage position and scale.
- Items outside the viewport are completely excluded from the React render tree.
- Exceptions: selected items, AI-animating items, and connector endpoints are
  always rendered (even if off-screen).

REACT.MEMO + CUSTOM EQUALITY:
- All 8 item components (Sticky, Rect, Circle, Line, Heart, Frame, Text) and
  ConnectorLine are wrapped in React.memo.
- Custom equality function boardItemEqual compares only render-relevant fields:
  x, y, width, height, fill, text, title, rotation, fontSize, points.
- Excludes createdBy, updatedAt — these don't affect rendering.

STRUCTURAL SHARING:
- The Firestore onSnapshot callback reuses object references for unchanged items.
- This means React.memo's shallow comparison works correctly — unchanged items
  keep the same reference and skip re-rendering.

STABLE CALLBACKS:
- handleTransformEnd is a useCallback (not recreated per render).
- handleItemClick uses boardItemsRef (a ref) to access items without including
  boardItems in its dependency array.

THROTTLING:
- Cursor broadcast: 16ms (60fps)
- Drag broadcast to RTDB: 50ms

STRESS TESTING:
- ?debug=1 query param adds a "Add 500 Items" button
- Uses src/lib/stressTest.ts to batch-create random items

KEY DETAIL FOR INTERVIEW:
"We use viewport culling with a 200px buffer to only render visible items.
React.memo with custom equality functions prevents re-renders for unchanged items.
Firestore's onSnapshot callback uses structural sharing — reusing object
references so memo comparisons work correctly. Cursor sync is throttled to 16ms.
We can verify 500+ object performance using the debug stress test button."


================================================================================
19. AI AGENT — ARCHITECTURE & AGENT LOOP
================================================================================

PRD Requirement: AI agent with 6+ distinct commands, multi-step execution.

WHERE IT LIVES:
- API route: src/app/api/ai-command/route.ts
- Tool definitions: src/lib/aiTools.ts
- Layout engine: src/lib/layoutEngine.ts
- Client UI: BoardClient.tsx (AI command bar)

CLIENT FLOW:
1. User opens AI command bar (Cmd+K or button)
2. Types a natural language command
3. Client serializes: command text, boardId, viewportBounds (current view area),
   viewportObjects (up to 50 visible items for context)
4. POSTs to /api/ai-command with Bearer token

SERVER FLOW:
1. Verify Firebase ID token
2. Write reservation doc (see section 22)
3. Build system prompt with board context + viewport info + active reservations
4. Enter agentic loop (up to 10 turns):
   a. Call Claude claude-sonnet-4-20250514 with max_tokens 4096
   b. If response contains tool_use blocks → execute each tool
   c. Accumulate tool results, feed back to Claude
   d. If response is text-only (no tool calls) → loop ends
5. Flush any pending Firestore writes via RestBatchWriter
6. Return { success, results[], createdIds[] }
7. Delete reservation doc (in finally block)

REST BATCH WRITER:
- The AI route does NOT use Firebase Admin SDK for writes. Instead, it uses a
  custom RestBatchWriter that makes individual PATCH/DELETE requests to the
  Firestore REST API using the user's ID token.
- Why: The Admin SDK's batchWrite requires service account OAuth2 scopes, but
  token verification only needs Google's public JWKS. This avoids requiring
  a service account for the AI feature.

KEY DETAIL FOR INTERVIEW:
"The AI agent uses an agentic loop — up to 10 turns of Claude calling tools and
receiving results. We use the Firestore REST API with the user's own token
instead of the Admin SDK to avoid needing service account credentials. This
was an intentional architectural choice to simplify deployment."


================================================================================
20. AI AGENT — TOOL SCHEMA (12 TOOLS)
================================================================================

PRD Minimum: 9 tools (createStickyNote, createShape, createFrame, createConnector,
moveObject, resizeObject, updateText, changeColor, getBoardState).

ACTUAL IMPLEMENTATION (12 tools in aiTools.ts):

CREATION TOOLS:
1. createStickyNote(text, x, y, color) — Create sticky at position with color
2. createShape(type, x, y, width, height, color) — Create rect/circle/line/heart
3. createFrame(title, x, y, width, height) — Create labeled frame
4. createConnector(fromId, toId, style) — Connect two items with line or arrow

MANIPULATION TOOLS:
5. moveObject(objectId, x, y) — Move item to new position
6. changeColor(objectId, color) — Update item fill color
7. resizeObject(objectId, width, height) — Update item dimensions
8. updateText(objectId, newText) — Update text/sticky content

QUERY TOOLS:
9. getBoardState() — Fetch all current board items (for AI context)

LAYOUT TOOLS:
10. arrangeInGrid(itemIds, columns, startX, startY, gap) — Arrange items in grid
    - Fetches real item sizes from Firestore
    - Uses computeGridLayout from layoutEngine.ts
    - Respects actual widths/heights for column/row sizing

TEMPLATE TOOLS:
11. createSWOTTemplate(centerX, centerY) — 4-quadrant SWOT analysis
12. createJourneyMap(centerX, centerY, stages) — Horizontal journey map
13. createRetroTemplate(centerX, centerY) — 3-column retrospective

TOOL EXECUTION:
- Most tools are synchronous — they queue writes in the RestBatchWriter.
- arrangeInGrid and template tools are async — they fetch data from Firestore,
  compute layouts, then queue writes.
- After each tool batch, the RestBatchWriter is flushed before the next turn.

KEY DETAIL FOR INTERVIEW:
"We have 13 tools total — exceeding the PRD's minimum of 9. The arrangeInGrid
tool is notable because it fetches actual item sizes from Firestore before
computing the layout, so items with different dimensions are arranged correctly.
Template tools use the layout engine for deterministic positioning."


================================================================================
21. AI AGENT — TEMPLATES (SWOT, JOURNEY MAP, RETRO)
================================================================================

SWOT TEMPLATE (createSWOTTemplate):
- Layout: 2x2 grid of frames with 24px gaps
- Each frame: 340x280
- Labels: Strengths (mint), Weaknesses (red), Opportunities (blue), Threats (yellow)
- computeSWOTLayout() returns positions for all 4 frames

JOURNEY MAP (createJourneyMap):
- Layout: Horizontal row of frames with connectors between them
- Dynamic number of stages (user specifies or AI decides)
- Each stage: 280x360
- Connectors: Arrow-style links between adjacent stages
- computeJourneyMapLayout() returns frame positions + connector metadata
  (fromIndex, toIndex pairs)

RETROSPECTIVE (createRetroTemplate):
- Layout: 3 vertical columns
- Labels: "What Went Well" (mint), "What Didn't" (red), "Action Items" (blue)
- Each column: 300x500
- computeRetroTemplate() returns positions for all 3 frames

ALL TEMPLATES:
- Use the viewport center as the anchor point
- Create multiple Firestore documents in a single batch
- Return createdIds for client-side animation

KEY DETAIL FOR INTERVIEW:
"Template tools use a deterministic layout engine — computeSWOTLayout,
computeJourneyMapLayout, computeRetroTemplate. These compute exact pixel
positions, ensuring consistent layouts regardless of viewport. The journey map
is dynamic — it accepts a variable number of stages and creates connectors
between adjacent stages."


================================================================================
22. AI AGENT — RESERVATION SYSTEM (CONCURRENCY)
================================================================================

PRD Requirement: Multiple users can issue AI commands simultaneously without conflict.

HOW IT WORKS:
1. Before calling the LLM, the API route writes a reservation doc to:
   boards/{boardId}/reservations/{reservationId}
   Content: { area: {x, y, w, h}, createdAt: timestamp }

2. Stale cleanup: Any existing reservations older than 30 seconds (RESERVATION_TTL_MS)
   are deleted.

3. Active reservations are passed to the LLM in the system prompt:
   "Active space reservations (avoid placing objects here): [{x, y, w, h}, ...]"

4. The LLM uses this information to place new objects OUTSIDE reserved areas,
   preventing two simultaneous AI commands from creating overlapping content.

5. In the finally block, the reservation is deleted after the agent completes.

EDGE CASES:
- If the server crashes, the 30-second TTL ensures stale reservations are cleaned
  up by the next AI command.
- If admin credentials aren't available (dev mode), the reservation system silently
  skips (try/catch with no-op).

KEY DETAIL FOR INTERVIEW:
"The reservation system is a spatial locking mechanism. Each AI command reserves
a viewport area, and the LLM prompt includes all active reservations so it avoids
those areas. This prevents two users' AI commands from creating overlapping
content. Reservations have a 30-second TTL as a safety net."


================================================================================
23. AI AGENT — CLIENT-SIDE ANIMATION
================================================================================

HOW IT WORKS:
- The API response includes createdIds[] — the IDs of all items the AI created.
- Client sets aiCreatedIds state with these IDs.
- A useEffect watches [aiCreatedIds, items]:
  1. For each createdId, look up the Konva.Group node in itemNodesRef
  2. If the node exists, animate it: start at opacity 0, scaleX/Y 0.88
  3. Tween to opacity 1, scaleX/Y 1 with stagger: item[i] starts at i * 100ms
  4. If node doesn't exist yet (Firestore snapshot hasn't arrived), the effect
     retries when items state updates (because items is in the dependency array)

NODE REGISTRATION:
- Each item component (StickyItem, RectItem, etc.) calls onGroupMount(id, node)
  in its useEffect, which stores the Konva.Group reference in itemNodesRef.
- React guarantees children's effects run before parent's effects, so by the time
  the animation effect runs, all item nodes are already registered.

KEY DETAIL FOR INTERVIEW:
"AI-created items animate in with a stagger effect — each item fades in and
scales up with a 100ms delay between items. The animation system uses a retry
pattern: if the Konva node isn't mounted yet when the effect runs, it retries
on the next Firestore snapshot when the items state updates."


