- Konva.js + react-konva (HTML5 Canvas rendering)

BACKEND:
- Next.js API Routes (serverless functions)
- Firebase Firestore (persistent data)
- Firebase Realtime Database (ephemeral presence/drag data)
- Firebase Authentication (Google OAuth)
- Firestore REST API (for AI route writes)

AI:
- Anthropic Claude (claude-sonnet-4-20250514)
- Agentic tool-use loop (up to 10 turns)
- 13 tools defined in aiTools.ts
- Layout engine for deterministic template positioning

DEPLOYMENT:
- Vercel (inferred from Next.js)
- Firebase project for backend services

BUILD:
- Turbopack (Next.js dev server)
- @opentelemetry/api as optional dependency (firebase-admin peer dep workaround)
- serverExternalPackages in next.config.ts for Firebase packages


================================================================================
25. QUICK-FIRE Q&A (LIKELY INTERVIEW QUESTIONS)
================================================================================

Q: Why Konva instead of DOM-based rendering?
A: Canvas rendering scales to 500+ objects without DOM node explosion. DOM-based
   rendering creates one element per object, causing layout thrashing and poor
   performance. Konva gives us a single <canvas> element with direct draw calls.

Q: Why Firestore AND Realtime Database?
A: Firestore for persistent data (items, connectors, boards) — it has strong
   consistency, complex queries, and offline support. RTDB for ephemeral
   high-frequency data (cursors, active drags) — it has lower latency and is
   cheaper for rapid writes. Different access patterns need different databases.

Q: How do you handle 500+ objects without lag?
A: Four techniques: (1) viewport culling — only render visible items plus 200px
   buffer, (2) React.memo with custom equality — skip re-renders for unchanged
   items, (3) structural sharing — reuse object references in Firestore listener,
   (4) stable callbacks — prevent unnecessary re-renders from handler recreation.

Q: How does your conflict resolution work?
A: Last-write-wins via Firestore. No custom CRDT or OT. For drags, we broadcast
   intermediate positions to RTDB so other users see smooth movement, then persist
   the final position to Firestore. All clients converge via onSnapshot.

Q: How does the AI agent handle multi-step commands?
A: Agentic loop — Claude receives tools, calls them, sees results, and can call
   more tools. Up to 10 turns. For example, "Create a SWOT analysis" triggers
   createSWOTTemplate which creates 4 frames. "Arrange items in a grid" calls
   getBoardState first to find items, then arrangeInGrid with their IDs.

Q: How do you prevent concurrent AI commands from conflicting?
A: Spatial reservation system. Each AI command writes a reservation doc with its
   viewport area. The LLM prompt includes all active reservations and instructs
   Claude to avoid those areas. 30-second TTL ensures cleanup.

Q: Why REST API instead of Firebase Admin SDK for AI writes?
A: Admin SDK's batchWrite requires service account OAuth2 scopes. Our token
   verification uses Google's public JWKS — no service account needed. Using the
   REST API with the user's token keeps the deployment simple and secure.

Q: How does presence survive network drops?
A: Three layers: (1) onDisconnect().remove() for clean drops, (2) 8-second
   heartbeat for ongoing connection proof, (3) 20-second stale TTL for edge
   cases. Combined, these ensure presence is always accurate within 20 seconds.

Q: Walk me through what happens when a user creates a sticky note.
A: User clicks "Add Sticky" → handleAddSticky() calculates viewport center in
   world coords → addDoc() writes to Firestore → onSnapshot fires on ALL clients
   → structural sharing check → StickyItem renders via React.memo → if it's an
   AI-created item, stagger animation plays via Konva node.to().

Q: How does your zoom work mathematically?
A: Pointer-relative zoom. Convert mouse position to world coordinates:
   worldPoint = (screenPoint - stagePos) / scale. Apply new scale. Reposition
   stage: newStagePos = screenPoint - worldPoint * newScale. This keeps the point
   under the cursor fixed while everything else scales around it.

Q: How do connectors know where to anchor on items?
A: getEdgePoint() calculates the intersection of the connector line with the
   item's perimeter. It uses the angle between item centers and the item's aspect
   ratio to determine which edge (top/bottom/left/right) the line exits from,
   then computes the exact intersection point on that edge.

Q: What happens if the AI agent crashes mid-execution?
A: The reservation is deleted in a finally block, so it's cleaned up regardless.
   Any items already written to Firestore persist (they're individual doc writes).
   The 30-second TTL ensures any orphaned reservation gets cleaned up by the next
   AI command. The client receives an error response and shows it to the user.

Q: How do you handle the text editing overlay?
A: We use HTML elements (textarea for stickies/text, input for frame titles)
   positioned absolutely over the Konva canvas. We compute the screen position
   by transforming the item's world coordinates through the current viewport
   transform (position + scale). On blur or Enter, the text persists to Firestore.

Q: What's your testing strategy for 5+ concurrent users?
A: Open 5+ browser windows/tabs to the same board. Each gets a unique session ID.
   The debug mode (?debug=1) provides a stress test button that creates 500 items
   to test rendering performance. Network throttling tests are done via Chrome
   DevTools to simulate poor connections.


